          "body": "The chapter opens with a brief and theologically charged sentence: Satan stood up against Israel and moved David to number Israel (21:1). Two agents act simultaneously — the adversary inciting and the king complying — yet the chapter holds David fully responsible. The parallel text in 2 Samuel 24:1 attributes the incitement to the LORD's anger against Israel, raising the deepest questions about divine permission, Satanic instrumentality, and human accountability. The Chronicler does not flatten this tension; he preserves both agents without resolving them philosophically.\n\nThe sin itself was not the act of counting but the motive behind it. Numbers 1 and 26 demonstrate that census-taking was divinely commanded for legitimate purposes. Exodus 30:12 required a half-shekel ransom when Israel was numbered, lest a plague break out — a provision conspicuously absent from David's census. But the deeper issue is what the count represented: David was numbering men who drew the sword (21:5), assessing his military manpower, trusting in human strength. Joab — not a man known for theological sensitivity — recognized it immediately as a cause of guilt (21:3). When Joab protests a moral issue, the alarm bells should be deafening. David overrides them.\n\nThe census result (1,100,000 in Israel; 470,000 in Judah) is the chapter's most ironic data point. These are massive numbers — impressive military strength. Yet within a week, 70,000 of those counted men will be dead (21:14), taken by the very plague that Exodus 30:12 warned would come if the ransom was not paid. The sword David trusted — counted, inventoried, catalogued — is answered by God's sword in the angel's hand, stretched over Jerusalem (21:16). What David numbered, God judged."
